Specimens in flower, especially those with smaller and narrower leaves, are more difficult to identify. The pedicels are short, with a persistent bract closely subtending the rigid calyx. The petals are narrow and densely pubescent on both surfaces. The anthers have more locelli, 20-24, than those of any other African species, and the staminal cone is dome-shaped with an even rim, completely enclosing the ovaries (Fig. 
35B
).
